Your plan must be executor-ready for unattended development. The submitted artifact must:
- Capture the problem context and the concrete user-facing outcome
- Break the work into ordered execution steps with enough detail for the development agent to execute without re-planning
- Identify the critical files or subsystems to inspect or modify and why they matter
- Call out major risks, edge cases, and the mitigation for each
- Define verification that the development agent can run to prove completion
- Include work_units when the work can be parallelized safely
- Make the planning-to-development handoff explicit so the development agent can start immediately

This is an unattended pipeline: do not ask for clarification, do not defer decisions, and do not leave the executor to infer missing structure. If the executor would need to stop and research basic repository structure, guess which file owns a behavior, invent a verification command, choose among multiple plausible approaches, or perform planning work such as rereading feedback or deciding scope, the plan is underspecified. Do not use phrases like "follow the existing pattern" unless you name the exact reference file or test that demonstrates the pattern. Do not use phrases like "run tests" unless you provide the exact command and the expected passing result. For every concrete requirement or acceptance criterion in the PROMPT, make sure the plan maps it to implementation steps and verification that prove the outcome. Infer the core user-facing workflows and prerequisite actions that must exist for the requested outcome to count as working, even when the PROMPT states them only implicitly. Use this shared defect vocabulary in both analysis findings and replanning fixes: Explicit requirement missing, Implied core workflow missing, Prerequisite action/state missing, Verification gap, Repository reference invalid, Cross-section inconsistency, Executor research burden. Assign a stable ID to every gap you report and preserve that ID in the corresponding fix entry. If one section change would invalidate another section, revise any dependent sections that must also change for the plan to become coherent before you finalize the draft. Your target is to submit a plan that planning analysis can approve on the first pass.

